<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="155" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,1328,2039]" pageId="18" pageNumber="155">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,490,1436,1462]" pageId="18" pageNumber="155">
Description of 
<typeStatus box="[381,490,1436,1462]" pageId="18" pageNumber="155">Holotype</typeStatus>
</emphasis>
. Colony unbranched or forks once at the node, with a thick and robust axis (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1638,1662]" captionTargetBox="[175,1410,181,1615]" captionTargetId="figure-19@19.[175,1411,181,1615]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 15. Dokidisis australis n. sp. holotype K3834, A, all collected and preserved colony pieces, B, in situ view of colony, C, view of individual polyp, and sclerites of, D, polyp body and tentacle rachis, E, coenenchyme, F, tentacle pinnules, G, pharynx." pageId="18" pageNumber="155">Fig. 15A, B</figureCitation>
). Only a portion of the colony was collected. The axis contains numerous longitudinal grooves and is 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="18" pageNumber="155" unit="mm" value="15.0">15 mm</quantity>
diameter at the basal section and 
<quantity box="[587,653,1508,1535]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="155" unit="mm" value="9.0">9 mm</quantity>
diameter in the distalmost portion of the colony. The hollow core is less than 
<quantity box="[255,320,1544,1571]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="155" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
in diameter at the base and increases slightly in diameter as the colony grows, reaching about 
<quantity box="[1372,1437,1544,1571]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="155" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
distally. Polyps are sparsely scattered on all sides of the axis, with large areas of thin coenenchyme between polyps. Sclerites in the polyp body are blunt rods, arranged longitudinally and obliquely (
<figureCitation box="[1073,1176,1616,1643]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1638,1662]" captionTargetBox="[175,1410,181,1615]" captionTargetId="figure-19@19.[175,1411,181,1615]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 15. Dokidisis australis n. sp. holotype K3834, A, all collected and preserved colony pieces, B, in situ view of colony, C, view of individual polyp, and sclerites of, D, polyp body and tentacle rachis, E, coenenchyme, F, tentacle pinnules, G, pharynx." pageId="18" pageNumber="155">Fig. 15C</figureCitation>
). Rods may be slightly curved, club-shaped, and vary in width (
<figureCitation box="[607,712,1652,1679]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1638,1662]" captionTargetBox="[175,1410,181,1615]" captionTargetId="figure-19@19.[175,1411,181,1615]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 15. Dokidisis australis n. sp. holotype K3834, A, all collected and preserved colony pieces, B, in situ view of colony, C, view of individual polyp, and sclerites of, D, polyp body and tentacle rachis, E, coenenchyme, F, tentacle pinnules, G, pharynx." pageId="18" pageNumber="155">Fig. 15D</figureCitation>
). Needles and scales are not present in the polyp body. Sclerites are sparsely and irregularly arranged throughout the coenenchyme in the form of flat rods, ranging in length from 
<quantity box="[151,338,1724,1751]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" metricValueMax="2.6" metricValueMin="1.4" pageId="18" pageNumber="155" unit="mm" value="0.2" valueMax="0.26" valueMin="0.14">0.14 to 0.26 mm</quantity>
(
<figureCitation box="[354,455,1724,1751]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1638,1662]" captionTargetBox="[175,1410,181,1615]" captionTargetId="figure-19@19.[175,1411,181,1615]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 15. Dokidisis australis n. sp. holotype K3834, A, all collected and preserved colony pieces, B, in situ view of colony, C, view of individual polyp, and sclerites of, D, polyp body and tentacle rachis, E, coenenchyme, F, tentacle pinnules, G, pharynx." pageId="18" pageNumber="155">Fig. 15E</figureCitation>
). Small flat rods, similar to those in the coenenchyme, may be sparsely arranged at the base of the polyp body as well. Scales are not present in the coenenchyme.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,1328,2039]" pageId="18" pageNumber="155">
Sclerites similar in shape to those in the polyp body but slightly smaller in size are arranged longitudinally along the aboral side (rachis) of the tentacles. Flat rods are arranged along the pinnules, perpendicular to the tentacle. Flat rods are decorated with numerous tubercles and longitudinal grooves (
<figureCitation box="[939,1039,1868,1895]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1638,1662]" captionTargetBox="[175,1410,181,1615]" captionTargetId="figure-19@19.[175,1411,181,1615]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 15. Dokidisis australis n. sp. holotype K3834, A, all collected and preserved colony pieces, B, in situ view of colony, C, view of individual polyp, and sclerites of, D, polyp body and tentacle rachis, E, coenenchyme, F, tentacle pinnules, G, pharynx." pageId="18" pageNumber="155">Fig. 15F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,1328,2039]" pageId="18" pageNumber="155">
Sclerites are very sparse in the pharynx, and several polyps had to be examined before any sclerites were found. The polyp pharynx lacks sclerites in the form of thorny rods or double stars. The two sclerites found in the pharynx were measured at 0.09 and 
<quantity box="[454,553,1976,2003]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="18" pageNumber="155" unit="mm" value="0.11">0.11 mm</quantity>
in length, with several longitudinal grooves and irregular borders (
<figureCitation box="[1297,1400,1976,2003]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1638,1662]" captionTargetBox="[175,1410,181,1615]" captionTargetId="figure-19@19.[175,1411,181,1615]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 15. Dokidisis australis n. sp. holotype K3834, A, all collected and preserved colony pieces, B, in situ view of colony, C, view of individual polyp, and sclerites of, D, polyp body and tentacle rachis, E, coenenchyme, F, tentacle pinnules, G, pharynx." pageId="18" pageNumber="155">Fig. 15G</figureCitation>
). It is possible that the sclerites found in the pharynx may be contaminants produced during dissection.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
