<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="156" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,1781,2023]" pageId="19" pageNumber="156">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1781,1807]" pageId="19" pageNumber="156">Etymology</emphasis>
. The species name is based on the Latin adjective 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lapointe &amp; Watling" authorityYear="2022" box="[898,996,1781,1807]" class="Anthozoa" family="Mopseidae" genus="Dokidisis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="19" pageNumber="156" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[898,996,1781,1807]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="156">australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
= southern, a reference to the southern hemisphere where the specimen was collected.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="157" pageId="19" pageNumber="156" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,1781,2023]" pageId="19" pageNumber="156">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1853,1879]" pageId="19" pageNumber="156">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lapointe &amp; Watling" authorityYear="2022" box="[321,531,1853,1879]" class="Anthozoa" family="Mopseidae" genus="Dokidisis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="19" pageNumber="156" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[321,531,1853,1879]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="156">Dokidisis australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Alderslade &amp; McFadden" authorityYear="2012" box="[674,883,1853,1879]" class="Anthozoa" family="Isididae" genus="Jasonisis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="19" pageNumber="156" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="thresheri">
<emphasis box="[674,883,1853,1879]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="156">Jasonisis thresheri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a new genus and species recently described from Tasmania (
<bibRefCitation author="Alderslade, P. &amp; McFadden, C. S." box="[271,640,1889,1915]" pageId="19" pageNumber="156" pagination="21 - 39" refId="ref8877" refString="Alderslade, P. &amp; McFadden, C. S. (2012) A new genus and species of the family Isididae (Coelenterata: Octocorallia) from a CMAR Biodiversity study, and a discussion on the subfamilial placement of some nominal isidid genera. Zootaxa, 3154 (1), 21 - 39. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3154.1.2" type="journal article" year="2012">Alderslade and McFadden, 2012</bibRefCitation>
), in that both species branch at the node and lack intertentacular needles and pharyngeal sclerites in the form of thorny rods or double stars.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1437,1781,2023]" lastBlockId="20.[151,1437,151,285]" lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="157" pageId="19" pageNumber="156">
However, unlike 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Alderslade &amp; McFadden" authorityYear="2012" box="[395,523,1961,1987]" class="Anthozoa" family="Isididae" genus="Jasonisis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="19" pageNumber="156" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="thresheri">
<emphasis box="[395,523,1961,1987]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="156">J. thresheri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lapointe &amp; Watling" authorityYear="2022" box="[538,672,1961,1987]" class="Anthozoa" family="Mopseidae" genus="Dokidisis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="19" pageNumber="156" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[538,672,1961,1987]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="156">D. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not covered by a thick tegument and the blunt rods in the polyp body differ significantly from the densely-packed scales in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Alderslade &amp; McFadden" authorityYear="2012" box="[824,927,1998,2023]" class="Anthozoa" family="Isididae" genus="Jasonisis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="19" pageNumber="156" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[824,927,1998,2023]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="156">Jasonisis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Besides the lack of pharyngeal sclerites, we could not determine a set of specific characters that would include 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lapointe &amp; Watling" authorityYear="2022" box="[900,1032,151,177]" class="Anthozoa" family="Mopseidae" genus="Dokidisis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="20" pageNumber="157" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[900,1032,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="157">D. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Alderslade &amp; McFadden" authorityYear="2012" box="[1182,1285,151,176]" class="Anthozoa" family="Isididae" genus="Jasonisis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="20" pageNumber="157" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1182,1285,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="157">Jasonisis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, even though the two species are in the same large J clade (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Watling, L. &amp; Heestand Saucier, E. &amp; France, S. C." box="[695,907,187,213]" pageId="20" pageNumber="157" pagination="337 - 375" refId="ref9546" refString="Watling, L. Heestand Saucier, E. &amp; France, S. C. (2022) Towards a revision of the bamboo corals: Part 4, delineating the family Keratoisididae. Zootaxa, 5093 (3), 337 - 375. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 5093.3.4" type="journal article" year="2022">Watling et al. 2022</bibRefCitation>
) (
<figureCitation box="[929,997,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[415,1180,182,1919]" captionTargetId="figure-19@3.[393,1195,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Cladogram of the Keratoisididae modified from Watling et al. (2022). New taxa added in this paper are in bold lettering. Bootstrap values&gt;50 are shown above the nodes and Bayesian probability values&gt;0.5 are shown below the nodes. Major clades are referred to by the designation along the right side of the cladogram." pageId="20" pageNumber="157">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). That clade has many morphologically diverse specimens within it and we suspect that with increased sampling the relationships of the several forms will become clear.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
